comments.text:
This will tell you if you might have OCD, If you are curious, read on :)


Unless you have physically gone to a doctor to prove it, you do not know 
for sure you have OCD. OCD is the mental illness with the most 
misconceptions about it. 

Learn more about OCD In Rhett and Lincs video on good mythical morning 
about OCD, and another one I recommend is on crash course psychology about 
OCD and generalized anxiety disorders.

I have been prescribed OCD by a trained phycologist and attend therapy, 
have studied the disorder, and can say positively I know I good deal about 
the illness

By what you have described, you do not sound like you have the disorder. 
OCD is characterized by unwanted repetitive thoughts. This may mean 
checking things over and over again due to extreme anxiety. Here's how it 
works out. 

The O stands for obsessive. You have unwanted thoughts generally fears or 
phobias about something. For me, it is I am afraid of me and my family 
being brutally murdered as the worst obsession. Others fear becoming so 
sick they die, leaving on their house burner and the house burning down, 
etc. these fears lead to the C

C stands for compulsions. Compulsions are rituals that temporarily help 
extreme anxiety brought on by phobias. For me, I check the doors 
repeatedly, sometimes hours at a time checking so that they are locked. I 
always fear the worst, and eve though I know the doors are locked, I get so 
afraid I check again. The same is with washing hands, laundry, surfaces, 
checking burners, etc to remove anxiety. 

The D means disorders. As you can see, this is a very complex mental 
disorder that effects millions of people, and the illness never goes away. 

Thank you whoever read this, I wish to inform the people who don't 
understand sufferers and that this is much more than being orderly. I used 
to think OCD was just being orderly before I was prescribed. I know some 
don't know better, but it still pains me to think people take this issue so 
lightly. 


Thank you :)

comments.text:
+Armin Arlert It can have physical and mental effects in the same way any 
anxiety attack can. Racing heart, inability to concentrate on anything 
other than the subject, nausea etc. And there is no limit. Some people are 
institutionalized over their OCD, "those hoodie strings, they are driving 
me insane" is a joke line from this song, but it can be true. It's 
interesting when two types mix, e.g. hoarding and organization. You get a 
house crammed full of stuff that is perfectly organized and polished 
weekly, toilet paper stacked to the celing in perfect columns, it's amazing 
to see when that one pops up. And it can affect health if they are 
overly-stressed on a subject- stress reduces life span. And there can also 
be compulsions that are bad for health, like needing to cut yourself (those 
are often the type to be institutionalized) or feeling the need to kick a 
certain object until your toes bleed or something. The possibilities are 
endless.

comments.text:
I have mild OCD. Not the kind where I want to fix things, but I have to do 
things in certain orders or I go fucking crazy. This manifests itself in me 
walking around buildings I'm familiar with in certain ways (to the door on 
the left, turn, then go back), touching doorknobs and walls in certain 
places (left wall, right wall, doorknob, right wall), weird internet habits 
(on youtube whenever I start a video I need to pause with the mouse, then 
press space to unpause it again in under a few seconds, or I need to do it 
again) cracking my knuckles in order(right index finger, ring finger, etc 
then left hand), switching lightswitches in certain ways even if they don't 
work (oops I switched the wrong one, I need to turn it off an on again 
three times), etc etc. When I see people who look at a pencil and 
straighten it, then see me watching, they'll look at me an say "oh, I have 
ocd!" and I want to fucking strangle them because I know I'm one of the 
lucky ones. Which is why I like this video, it pokes fun at those people.

comments.text:
A very common misconception about obsessive compulsive disorder is that 
it's about organisation and cleaning. Generally speaking a lot of people 
that suffer from it have it to do with things such as that but that's 
simply the tip of the iceberg. It can be any compulsive action from not 
moving until 7:50 or washing your hands until they tear the skin off and 
bleed. It very often has little to do with reason, such as organising 
shelves because they aren't in order. Almost all human beings show 
behaviour like that to a degree, some more than others and it's this 
difference along with social environments that has produced such 
self-diagnosis in this generation

comments.text:
OCD takes on many forms. Yes, some things that seem "OCD," or  what we call 
"OCD" might actually not be, and the only way to know for sure is to be 
diagnosed by a psychologist or psychiatrist, but the key is to have an 
obsession (unwanted thoughts/feelings, which can include wanting things to 
be orderly) and an associated compulsion (must fix all the things!) that 
the person doesn't want to perform, but can't seem to stop (the classic 
example is excessive washing of the hands,) but again, it can be unique to 
that person! 

http://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/topics/obsessive-compulsive-disorder-ocd/index.shtml

comments.text:
I have both, is the thing. I distinctly have both. So, I mean you more 
likely have obsessive tendencies, or both or are confusing the necessary 
rigidity of expectations that often is part of being autistic with OCD. 
They are definitely two separate things. I know this because I am able to 
much of the time differentiate between the two when an issue comes up. I 
also know this because I know people who have one or the other, or who also 
have both. I also know this because I have studied psychology for over a 
decade and understand that though they both involve a certain need and 
demand of rigid expectations and there is disruption when that isn't met, 
the reason for the need and demand is different. Also, the expected 
consequences [from the individual with the need/demand] and the reality of 
the consequences [both what actually happens as a result and the feelings 
and behaviors of the individual] tend to be very different. 

It can be extremely frustration when people put forth misinformation- its 
not only just frustrating because psychology is my 'thing' [see: special 
interest and brains, neurology, abnormal psych, psychiatry, biology] but 
also it can down the line be harmful. I'm not saying you don't experience 
both. What I *am* saying is what you are telling people specifically is 
wrong.
comments.author: Joelle Marie

comments.text:

part of my Autism, so I am speaking for myself. I despise it when I meet

comments.text:
+SaySay Lona So... Yeah, about this: " If you actually had OCD, you 
probably wouldn't be on the internet because there are so many idiots here 
that spell things wrong and nothing is just-so."  About that idiots on the 
internet thing... let's start with that. I have OCD. I have some pretty 
fucking nasty OCD. I am actually pretty vocal about it- you demonstrate a 
really great reason why. Actually the majority of the comments in this 
comment section do.

People tend to be ignorant as hell about OCD. I'm not supposed to be on the 
internet because typos will send me into a mental breakdown of epic 
proportions, and that is the assumption of all these morons WrITiNG liKe 
thIS, but then it doesn't occur to them that if I am someone with OCD who 
is triggered so easily maybe I actually control what I expose myself to. 
Because I don't want to be driven crazy by idiots who are cruel and 
ignorant about the true detrimental effect that kind of thing can have.

So all of you who are bitching and moaning about having OCD and how those 
stupidly typed comments are "torture", maybe think about how questionable 
your complaints of agony are at this point. Either that, or if that's 
really the case, consider taking more control of your life: you probably 
encounter typos galore on the internet- maybe be more discerning about 
where you spend your time so you can maintain some stability for yourself.

Back to "People with OCD aren't going to go around and tell everyone that 
they have OCD, because they aren't proud of it."  I have to ask: do you 
have OCD, +SaySay Lona ?  I talk about my OCD. People are not proud of 
their OCD symptoms, true. But when they find out it's OCD, and not some 
personal horrible fault in themselves, the idea is to figure out how to 
deal with it. Not be ashamed and hide. Some people don't talk about it. 
 Kind of like some people with OCD are truly triggered by grammar errors 
[and maybe we should all understand what an actually trigger is, as opposed 
to "annoyance"]. Some people talk about it freely, some people are 
self-advocates. Some people don't buy into the whole "I should be ashamed" 
thing. Some people don't give two shits about grammar beyond the "you seem 
like a moron when you use text speak as though it is a legitimate dialect" 
issue. 

I mean, in short: don't speak for me.

comments.text:
+chloe huang That is generally not what OCD is. OCD = Obsessive compulsive 
disorder, so, when a certain thing isn't right/you did something that 
triggers your OCD, you will have to do something to fix it, every time that 
thing occurs.

I've seen people with OCD that, if they were ever to look at their right 
toe, they'd have to concentrate on it so long until something distracts 
them. And that would, in that case, happen every time they look at their 
right toe, which may take up to 6 hours. THAT IS what OCD is.

What most people here have is OCT, Obsessive compulsive tensions, so you 
tend to do something when something else happens, for example get picky 
over something being asymmetric, or simply having to fix a picture that 
might be off-center.

out" just shut the hell up, you don't know shit. I've been dealing with 
this shit for a long time now and it irritates me so fucking much when 
people think they do have a disorder when they dislike un-even numbers, 
It's probably in our nature! OCD isn't just with numbers, it's a lot more 
to it than that, a lot unexplainable stuff. I had/have to go in and out of 
my door and it can take up to some hours because I have to have specific 
thoughts when I do it and all that stuff. Also, the worst part in which I 
was hospitalized for was because of my extreme fear of germs. I wouldn't 
even swallow my own spit if I heard/saw people talking like 60 meters away. 
I would ONLY eat food from fabrics and no hand made stuff. I am 15, my 
weight is 35-36kg and I am around 1.60cm tall. Tkae a look at this:

Obsession – your mind is overwhelmed by a constant obsessive fear or 
concern, such as the fear your house will be burgled.

Anxiety – this obsession provokes a feeling of intense anxiety and distress.

Compulsion – you adopt a pattern of compulsive behaviour to reduce your 
anxiety and distress, such as checking all your windows and doors are 
locked at least three times
before leaving the house.

Temporary relief – the compulsive behaviour brings temporary relief from 
anxiety but the obsession and anxiety soon return, causing the cycle to 
begin again.

The hospital couldn't keep me in because they didn't know what to do with 
me, I was too "bad" for them to even try. I got sent home after 1 or 2 
days, I can't remember.

I could go on for hours talking about all my compulsions and obsessions and 
all that shit, which probably takes up like 85/100 of my day. But I'd 
rather not as people will see that as "bragging" about my disorder.

So, please, think before you comment.﻿

top_comment.text:
OCD doesn't just have to be things like letters being different sizes (and 
I'm not talking about the video here, I'm talking about the people who have 
commented). I have symmetry and order OCD, which means that if I do 
something with one hand, I must do it with the other. If I scratch my right 
leg, I have to scratch my left one too, in the exact same way. Also once I 
have said words I might repeat them over and over in my head. Also feeling 
the need to touch certain things - there is more, but I won't go into 
everything. My point is, there are four main categories of OCD, and things 
like this are usually what people and society focuses on - when it's a lot 
wider than that.﻿

All these people have no idea what OCD is... I'm not talking about the 
video but the comments. People with obsessive compulsive disorder don't 
"get tortured" by idiots playing around with caps lock. They obsess over 
something, usually something tangible and immediate around them that in 
their minds they cant stop obsessing over which drives them to try and do 
something about it ( which its why its fucking called obsessive- 
compulsive). Its not trying to be neat and tidy... its not acting like you 
always need to correct someones bad internet grammar (most of you don't 
even correct any other type of grammar besides fucking contractions). Its 
things like feeling so dirty all the time you need to clean your hands or 
sanitize them every moment you feel like something contaminated may have 
come in contact with your hands. Another common behavior is having the need 
to count things to a common number or color, usually driven by 
superstitions regarding that number or color. Please people quit making an 
ass of yourself on the internet. 
Anyways great video guys. ﻿

comments.text:
First off just want to say I don't have OCD and don't know what its like, I 
however do feel urges to fix small things I only assume this is just a 
natural human function to attempt to correct mistakes or details. And my 
small understanding of OCD is basically a much more extreme version of 
this, to the point where your motives are almost no longer voluntary. I see 
a lot of the time on places, such as twitch or youtube, that there are 
people that make comments such as "you're driving my OCD crazy." As well as 
I see people that state from their own POV  and how real OCD effects their 
life. I could honestly careless about the first group, that is pure 
ignorance of the definition of OCD or just a attention magnet gig. What 
gets me is seeing people that critique the people that state they have been 
diagnosed. In my opinion it is better to say 'I'm sorry for you' (which by 
the way I am Paul) to someone that is faking rather than try to disprove 
someone who could potentially be in reality ruined by OCD. In all I 
honestly wish for a lot of the fighting about whether or not they actually 
have it to stop. I however am not approving people to jump around saying 
they have been diagnosed when they haven't, as well as I think it is fine 
to critique if you are giving medical/mental advice or help to said person. 
Again I don't have OCD and I don't plan on getting checked for one either. 
But I will say this, those that don't have it be nice don't post hurtful 
breakdowns of someone else's POV or attempt to fake it (for the huge amount 
of good things that absently rewards) and those who do shouldn't need to 
argue their position. The internet might be a huge place with a lot of mean 
people but it doesn't hurt to make it slightly more friendly. :D

comments.text:
+TheKRWill I was clinically diagnosed for OCD 10 years ago with germaphobic 
like symptoms. OCD isn't just checking an unreasonable amount to make sure 
everything looks right, it can appear in many different ways, fear of 
getting sick being one of them. OCD consists of an obsessive thought that 
will recur and persist despite efforts to ignore them (the "O"). The 
obsessions require a compulsion to give relief and feeling of safety (The 
"C"). His obsession is germs, he cannot stop thinking about them even 
though at many times it is probably very unreasonable. The compulsion that 
follows is sanitizing, or avoiding things that aren't really contaminated 
although the brain makes it out to seem that way. From personal experience, 
I missed out on birthday parties, amusement parks, going out with friends, 
there was even a point where I was so overwhelmed with thoughts of 
contamination everywhere, that I locked myself in my room, and only got out 
to eat, and use the bathroom for 3 days at a time. And just because 
medication doesn't work doesn't mean anything. Sometimes medication doesn't 
work on some people, that doesn't mean he doesn't have it. Look at some 
people like Howie Mandell (if I that's the right spelling of his name), he 
has OCD surrounded around germs as well. I don't know if you have OCD, if 
you do I am sorry and hope that you are able to get better.
comments.author: MopyMoose

just O.C.D. that makes it go that far.

I have a "friend" with severe O.C.D. and she can't do a single thing 
without having a ritual for it. 
The other part of her diagnosis is paranoid schizophreniac. So her O.C.D. 
is just her way of staying away from stuff that trigger the schizophrenia. 
But when it's triggered (by not allowed to complete a ritual or fix 
something that bothers her) she gets paranoid, delusional and suicidal. 
This has been developed over 40 years. she has never gotten any help for it.
So as +DucksUnlimited is saying. It could happen but it's very rare. And 
people this bad is usually locked up and monitored in a safe environment.

comments.text:
I don't think that you have OCD ;), that's perfectly normal. With OCD, 
(please correct me if I'm wrong, I'm no expert) an extreme inner negative 
tension (fear, depression, aggression) causes you to perform unreasonable 
actions which seem to soothe the negativeness of your psychological 
problems, like to wash the dirt off or assort things always and everywhere. 
This action then gets like a drug, although it has "positive" effects, you 
also get incapable of stopping performing the action and the disorder will 
stop you of living a normal life.
What you are experiencing is just your brain trying to entertain you during 
boredom :).

comments.text:
All the "OCD shots" are is a large dose of vitamin b12. If you've been 
professionally diagnosed, like I have, this isn't even an option they bring 
up for even severe OCD. That is because it is not proven to work (It's 
really a personal choice that may work, or, at least, give a placebo 
effect. There are no laws against it, and you can even just buy a ton of 
b12 tablets from walmart.). Instead of getting an unnecessary prodding from 
a stranger, I was just prescribed with anxiety medication because anxiety 
is really a large part behind OCD. You may not agree, but personally, some 
vitamin isn't going to stop me from brushing my teeth bloody.

top_comment.text:
You don't have OCD just because something is off-center or off-balance, and 
that bothers you. It is usually a compulsion to do something specific (But 
it could also vary, for example, people who have to wash your hands a dozen 
times a week. My heart goes out to you) For example, every time I leave a 
room, I need to sit down in the seat I was sitting in and stand up twice 
before I can leave. However, this is only a single obsessive compulsion. My 
grandmother, however, has to go through dozens of rituals every single day 
of her life, because she actually has OCD. So please... stop being ignorant 
and saying "Lololol I like things clean, and I dislike when things are 
uneven! LOLOL I have OCD, I am such a little special snowflake!" because 
when you self diagnose yourself, you only make yourself seem like a prick 
to people who actually suffer through this disease and their families.  ﻿

top_comment.text:
The comments on this particular video are even more ignorant than usual. : /
Okay, children, time for some education.
I'll try to keep it simple.

OCD is an anxiety disorder meaning, when something triggers it, they feel 
sick, irritated, angered, fearful, nervous, etc.
http://www.ocduk.org/types-ocd (here are a few types.)
There are MANY potential OCD triggers and people can have it to a large or 
small degree.  So the font thing may or may not bother someone with OCD but 
if it does you could literally be making them feel ill.

If you don't think it is a serious disorder then you haven't seen a person 
with OCD before because it is both sad and disturbing.  Compulsive behavior 
can lead to some really nasty injuries and even death (in the case of 
hoarding particularly).
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/26/Dermatophagia.jpg

The causes are pretty interesting (numerous) but there is a link between 
OCD and traumatic brain injuries- like car crashes and strokes.
http://www.ocduk.org/what-causes-ocd
In short it's a very REAL thing.  It's physical.

If you don't understand it do some reading instead of laughing.
Mental illnesses make your life SUCK.﻿

comments.text:
*To everyone in this comment section who said things for the purpose of 
hurting people with OCD please please please read*
Seriously? I can tell none of you have ever had or known someone whose had 
a mental disorder. It's terrible. It can ruin your life. I've had numerous 
mental disorders, and it's not one of those things that make you feel 
special and happy, it makes you feel alone and hated. Therapy isn't some 
walk in the park either. It's 1-2 hours of intense mental pain while trying 
to face your worst fear. When people have phobias or disorders, the thing 
that they're afraid of goes through the same part of your emotional, or 
"animal" brain that processes fatal encounters. Seeing things like what you 
guys are posting feels the *exact* same way to them as having a lion jump 
out of the bushes, and that feeling of pure fear you get because you know 
you're going to die feels to you, if not worse. You *will* give them a 
panic attack. And for those of you who've never had a panic attack (which 
clearly none of you have) you feel all of these VERY intensely:
-Shortness of breath or hyperventilation
-Heart palpitations or a racing heart
-Chest pain or discomfort
-Trembling or shaking
-Choking feeling or lack of oxygen
-Feeling unreal or detached from your surroundings
-Sweating
-Claustrophobia or feeling of being trapped
-Nausea or upset stomach
-Feeling dizzy, light-headed, or faint
-Numbness or tingling sensations
-Hot or cold flashes
-Feeling of dying, losing control, or going crazy from fear alone
And it's terrible. I've never felt any physical pain that amounts to it. 
And I've been stung by a sting ray, jellyfish, and broken bones. And by 
doing what you're doing, you're giving someone a panic attack. And it lasts 
10-30 minutes. And it's all your fault. So congratulations, I hope you all 
feel proud of yourself. I hope that knowing that by ruining someone else 
day you've in some sick way made yours better. It's because of people like 
you that we have to be ashamed of our disorders. People like you made me 
switch schools because of how many people exploited my phobia. People like 
you drive people like me to suicide. But none of you will even give your 
comment a second though, let alone delete it. In fact, I bet none of you 
even had the decency to read this, but if you have, and you delete your 
comment and never post one like that again, I totally and completely 
forgive you. Sorry for the rant, I just needed to do something about all 
the people in these comments. And if I get just one person to delete their 
comment, all the time I spent typing this will be 100% worth it. Thank you 
for reading this.
comments.author: Kate Oxley

comments.text:
To give you a broader answer, the issue with OCD is the C. OCD stands for 
Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder. It basically means that somewhere in our 
brains, a filter is missing, causing actions or events not to be processed 
as complete. This leads to an OBSESSION (that is actually strong enough to 
warrant all-caps) with the action or event. In order to cope with the 
obsession, we have compulsions, which can range from organizing to 
hand-washing to any number of things. The reason so many people with OCD 
act like it's a serious problem is because it is, at least in many cases, 
uncontrollable and far more severe. We hate OCD because it forces us into a 
lifestyle without choice. We are basically being held hostage by our own 
minds.

comments.text:
Very well...you asked for it.

Perfectionists, obviously, have already been displayed in the video. 

OCD is something completely different, but its symptoms can manifest in 
different ways, from contamination to repetitive rituals.

Let's take a look at contamination: Imagine if *EVERYTHING* in your life 
was 'contaminated' aside from a few select things, such as perhaps your 
room, your personal possessions, and a close friend or two.

Why is this so bad? Because if you touch something or someone that's 
contaminated, the part that touched it is contaminated. Depending on how 
'badly' you think it's contaminated would measure your reaction. Along with 
a panic attack, of course, you might want to do something as far as 
amputate that body part or wash it for two hours straight with water so hot 
that you wouldn't be able to feel your hand for days.

I know this seems odd and foreign to you – and people with OCD know it, but 
the thoughts don't go away. The thoughts can be so powerful that they 
completely override your pain threshold or even your survival instincts.

This was only an example of one form of OCD, and of course there are many 
more, but this is probably one of my most personal
comments.author: Stone Keyboard

+Courtney F Not all OCD has ritual/repetitive symptoms. The O is the 
obsession - the "Oh No" what is going to go wrong. The "Oh No" is usually 
very scary/bad thoughts...like death, injury, etc. Sometimes the fixes (the 
Compulsions) are rituals, sometimes they are avoidance. It is a tough 
stereotype to break that OCD is always manifested by the examples of 
keeping things in order.
comments.author: Cynthia Hollenberger

comments.text:
Not gonna lie, that doesn't sound like OCD. Sounds like germaphobia and 
don't get me wrong, I hold my breath if someone coughs or sneezes near me 
in public. I also can't stand to eat food that's been in the fridge for 
longer than one day (leftovers) because it doesn't taste fresh and I get 
all weirded out about it spoiling. But these are mainly preferences or 
habits (which can be broken or ignored) whereas OCD is more brutal, like 
you cannot leave the house without washing your hands 3 times in a row, 
even if the stove is on fire. Though there's milder cases of OCD, but I 
don't think anyone WANTS to have OCD so here's to hoping I may have put 
your mind at ease a little bit? :P

comments.text:
+Joshposh2012 What people think is OCD is really OCPD. OCD is having 
nagging thoughts or feelings or fixations (obsessions), which drive a 
behavior (compulsions) to satisfy the conditions of or relieve anxiety 
regarding these obsessions. Namely, cleaning your hands or your personal 
belongings dozens to HUNDREDS of times a day to make sure you aren't 
contaminated. Or people who hoard things in obscene quantities. Or people 
who quite literally operate on patterns. 

OCPD is a strict adherence to rules, need for perfectionism, cleanliness, 
organization, etc. But to the point where it essentially dominates your 
life, not just a little quirk like people describe.
comments.author: Rina Berman

comments.text:
The math in the riddle is incorrect. They paid $30 collectively. $5 were 
taken away leaving $25 in the pool. Of those $5 taken away, $2 were used to 
pay the tip and 3 were returned meaning $27 were collectively paid. Which 
means that $25 went towards paying for the night which is not divisible by 
three therefore they did not contribute equally to the *rent.* However 
since the manager took $2 they actually paid $27 which is divisible by 
three meaning they each contributed $9. Add to the $27 the $3 that were 
returned and you get back to the $10 they each paid in the beginning. The 
$2 *cannot* be added to the $27 paid because it is *part* of the $27 
dollars paid, only $25 actually went towards the rent. Therefore, the math 
in the riddle is incorrect.

There is no missing dollar.

comments.text:
I used to have the same problem with touching peoples' hands a long time 
ago. Medication helps some, but what helps the most is a pair of gloves. If 
I ever go to a store or to class or any other place where I know things I 
will be touching have been touched by other people, I just wear a pair of 
thin gloves. Once you learn how to put on/take off gloves without having to 
touch the surface of the gloves, your anxiety about contamination will 
decrease--at least, mine did. The only problem I have now is the issue of 
washing gloves since eventually dirt and dead germs/skin cells will 
accumulate on the surface of the gloves and on the interior. I found that 
spraying anti-germ liquids that have a lemon or bleach smell allows me to 
feel better about my gloves being sanitary.

comments.text:
Kinda, though that is pushing more to the side of OCPD 
(Obsessive-Compulsive Personality Disorder).
Which usually makes an extreme perfectionist, who wants everything in 
order, etc.
Though people with OCD (Obsessive-Compulsive DIsorder) tend to do some 
stuff like that. Like, repetitive behaviors (washing hands frequently, 
repetitive checking, doing some things always in the same order, and so on).
But the worst part of OCD, at least for me, is having to fight against 
these intrusive thoughts.
These two have some really similar symptoms, so it's really easy to confuse 
them.
Of course, you can instead of trust me, search or ask people who know more 
about this, I'm just someone who has that.
comments.author: Carlos Daniel Ferrer
